🚪 Act I: The Beginning
The Protagonist (The Traveler)
Characteristics: Silent, driven, and desperate. They never look back and refuse to stand still, propelled by an unnamed running guilt or grief. They represent the player's own avoidance.

Appearance: Clad in a heavy, travel-worn cloak with the hood pulled up, obscuring their face in shadow. Their boots are caked in thick mud, and their posture is slightly hunched, as if carrying an invisible, crushing weight on their shoulders.

Role: The vessel for the player's journey.


The Old Man
Characteristics: Cryptic, weary, and stationary. He serves as the final warning system before the traveler enters the psychological trap of the road. He speaks in riddles because he already understands the true nature of the loop.

Appearance: An ancient, frail figure sitting on a rotting wooden log beside the milestone. He is dressed in tattered, colorless rags that blend almost perfectly into the gray dirt of the road. His eyes are milky and blind, and his hands are deeply calloused and stained with earth.

Role: Delivers the foundational warning: “You’re walking away, not forward.”


🏚️ Act II: The Empty World (Waystation 1 & 2)
The Distant Figure / Shadowy Figure
Characteristics: Elusive, patient, and perfectly synchronized. It acts as a beacon, constantly drawing the player forward under the illusion of progress or guidance. It never attacks; it simply waits.

Appearance: A stark, featureless silhouette silhouetted against the horizon. In the twilight of Act II, it appears as a dark smudge on the edge of the fog. By Act III, it takes on a more distinct shape, perfectly mirroring the height and cloak outline of the Protagonist.

Role: The psychological carrot on a stick. It is later revealed to be the traveler's own projected shadow.


Old Martha (The Husk)
Characteristics: Peaceful but tragic. She is the embodiment of what happens when a traveler finally loses the will to walk but refuses to face their past. She chose physical death over psychological movement.

Appearance: Found in House 3 of Waystation 1. She is not a gruesome corpse, but rather a perfectly preserved, dried-out wooden husk of an old woman sitting in a rocking chair. Her skin looks like pale parchment, and she is clutching an iron key tightly against her hollow ribcage.

Role: Holds the key to progress; her final letter explains that the road simply "forgets" those who stop.


The Reflection (The Lagging Mirror)
Characteristics: Terrified, trapped, and hyper-aware. It represents the true, vulnerable human self that the traveler is trying to outrun.

Appearance: Visible inside the Silver Mirror in the church confessional box of Waystation 2. While the player character looks stoic, the reflection's hood is down, revealing a face twisted in silent horror. Its movements lag exactly one second behind the player, desperately staring out through the glass.

Role: A direct warning that the traveler's soul is being left behind the further they walk.


🏛️ Act III: The Truth of the Road (Waystation 3)
The Phantom Travelers
Characteristics: Mindless, hollow, and uniform. They are the remnants of millions of people across centuries who chose the "Keep Walking" ending. They have lost all individuality.

Appearance: Visible only during the midnight tolling of the self-ringing church bell. They are translucent, ash-gray silhouettes of people from different time periods (Roman soldiers, Victorian peasants, modern figures). They all walk with their heads bowed in perfect, mechanical unison, staring blindly at the dirt.

Role: Foreshadows the eternal cycle of the road and what the protagonist will become if they refuse to stop.


⚖️ Final Act: Choice
The New Traveler
Characteristics: Naive, hopeful, and exhausted. They are the next link in the endless chain of the road, arriving right as the protagonist's journey ends.

Appearance: Only visible if the player chooses the "Keep Walking" ending. They appear at the bottom of the screen as a small, dimly lit silhouette entering the final clearing. Their clothes are identical to the Protagonist's clothes at the start of Act I.

Role: They look up at the Protagonist (who has now become the static, featureless Distant Figure), cementing the cyclical tragedy of the endless road.
